  "body": "## Idempotency first\n\nA script that is safe to run twice is worth far more than a script that is fast to write once. Before automating a manual process, ask what happens if the script runs again against a system already in the target state — a good automation script checks state before changing it, rather than assuming a blank slate.\n\n## Prefer explicit over clever\n\n`Get-Something | Where-Object { ... } | ForEach-Object { ... }` reads clearly to the next person — often future me — who has to maintain it. Dense one-liners that chain many pipeline stages together save a few lines but cost far more time the next time something breaks and someone has to figure out which stage failed.\n\n## Log what changed, not just that something ran\n\nA script that only prints \"Done\" is much harder to trust in production than one that prints exactly what it found, what it decided to change, and what it actually changed. `-WhatIf` support and a real change log are worth building in from the start, not retrofitted after the first incident caused by a script that changed more than expected.\n\n## Treat credentials as a first-class design constraint\n\nAutomation that \"just works\" by embedding a credential directly in a script is a liability the moment that script is shared, copied, or version-controlled. Deciding how a script authenticates — a managed identity, a credential store, an interactive prompt — is a design decision to make before writing the first line of logic, not an afterthought.\n\n## Small, composable scripts over one large script\n\nA single automation script that tries to do everything becomes the hardest thing in the environment to safely change. Several small, single-purpose scripts that can be tested and run independently are easier to reason about, easier to hand off, and easier to replace one at a time as requirements change."
